summary:
The Council noted with grave concern the continued threat posed by ISIL, Ansar Al Charia, and other individuals and groups associated with Al-Qaida operating in Libya, and reaffirmed its resolve to address all aspects of that threat. 

It also expressed concern at the increased use of new information and communication technologies, in particular the Internet, by terrorists and their supporters for recruitment and incitement to commit terrorist acts.
Commending the efforts of the Special Representative of the Secretary-General to facilitate a political solution to the crisis in Libya, 
Reaffirming its commitment to Libya's sovereignty, independence, territorial integrity and national unity, 
1. Condemns terrorist acts by ISIL, groups aligned with ISIL, Ansar Al Charia, and Al-Qaida affiliates in Libya; 
2. Stresses implementation of resolutions 1267, 1373, 1624, 1989, 2161, 2170, 2174, 2178, 2195, and 2199, including against ISIL and Al-Qaida affiliates; 
3. Urges Member States to combat terrorist threats in Libya under the UN Charter and International Law; 
4. Encourages listing requests to the 1267 Committee for individuals and entities supporting ISIL, Ansar Al Charia, and Al-Qaida; 
5. Vows to consider listing those financing, arming, or supporting ISIL, Ansar Al Charia, and Al-Qaida; 
6. Reaffirms that counter-terrorism measures must comply with international law, particularly human rights, refugee, and humanitarian law; 
7. Calls on the 1970 Committee to expedite requests for arms transfers to the Libyan Government to combat terrorists; 
8. Emphasizes providing security and capacity-building assistance to the Libyan Government; 
9. Urges Member States to help build capacity to address ISIL and Al-Qaida threats; 
10. Supports Libyan Government efforts to combat ISIL and Al-Qaida; 
11. Recognizes the roles of the African Union, League of Arab States, and Libya's neighbors in finding a peaceful solution; 
12. Supports UN-led political dialogue between Libyan parties; 
13. Directs the Analytical Support and Sanctions Monitoring Team to report on the terrorism threat; 
14. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
